a very small wing loading was able to remain in the air longer than normally
possible, especially considering that since it no longer had loads on it but its
own, it was well balanced for developing a decent unguided glide slope. In the
case of the TWA 800 situation, the wing was heavily loaded in the rear, which
caused its initial pitch up and eventual stallout at 17000 feet. The stallout
